      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Asbestos in Brisbane Homes: What Sellers Must Know Before Listing
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Most pre-1990 Brisbane homes contain asbestos in some form. Here is what that means for your sale, your disclosure obligations, and how to handle it without overreacting.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>If your Brisbane home was built before 1990, there is a reasonable probability that asbestos-containing materials are present somewhere in the building. This is not a reason to panic, and it is not a reason to delay or abandon a sale. It is a reason to understand what you are dealing with, disclose it properly, and make a sensible decision about how to handle it before you list. Sellers who approach asbestos calmly and practically almost always get a better result than those who either ignore it or overreact to it.</p>

      <p>Asbestos was used widely in Australian residential construction from the 1940s through to the mid-1980s. The most common locations in Brisbane homes are fibro cement sheeting used in walls and cladding, eaves lining, wet area linings (bathroom and laundry walls), internal wall linings in older granny flats and secondary structures, some floor tiles and floor tile adhesives, and roofing materials in certain post-war construction types. In Brisbane's inner east, the period Queenslander and the post-war fibro home are the two property types where asbestos most commonly appears.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Bonded versus friable: the distinction that matters</h2>
      <p>Not all asbestos carries the same risk profile or the same implications for a sale. The critical distinction is between bonded asbestos and friable asbestos.</p>

      <p>Bonded asbestos (also called non-friable asbestos) is asbestos that is held firmly within a cement or resin matrix. Fibro sheeting is the classic example. When it is intact and in reasonable condition, bonded asbestos poses a very low risk because the fibres cannot become airborne during normal use. It can be safely left in place, identified in an asbestos register, and managed over the life of the building. This is the type most commonly found in Brisbane residential properties, and most experienced buyers in the inner east expect to encounter it in pre-1990 homes.</p>

      <p>Friable asbestos is asbestos that can be crumbled or reduced to powder by hand pressure. This type was used less commonly in residential construction, but it turns up occasionally in pipe lagging, some insulation applications, and older thermal products. Friable asbestos in poor condition is treated very differently from bonded sheeting: it requires licensed removal, it can affect finance approval and insurance, and it does narrow the buyer pool more materially. If your building or pest inspector reports friable asbestos, the appropriate response is to get a remediation quote before listing, understand the cost, and factor that into your pricing and disclosure strategy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure obligations in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Queensland does not have a specific statutory obligation requiring sellers to disclose the presence of asbestos in a residential property the way some other Australian states do. There is no mandatory asbestos disclosure item on the standard property law form. However, this does not mean you can simply stay silent on the subject.</p>

      <p>Sellers and their agents have a general obligation not to make misleading representations to buyers, and agents are required to disclose known material facts. If you are aware that asbestos is present in your property, whether through a previous asbestos assessment, prior renovation work, or your own knowledge, and you do not disclose that to buyers, you risk a claim that you withheld a material fact. The practical standard most conveyancers apply is straightforward: if you know it is there, disclose it.</p>

      <p>The most defensible position is to commission a licensed asbestos assessor to prepare an asbestos register before you list. This document identifies what materials are present, where they are located, and what condition they are in. It can then be made available to buyers during due diligence. Buyers who know exactly what they are dealing with are less likely to use asbestos as a lever to negotiate aggressively or exit the contract, because the uncertainty has been removed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What building and pest inspectors report and how buyers react</h2>
      <p>Building and pest inspectors routinely identify suspected asbestos-containing materials and note them in their reports. The standard report language is usually something like: "fibro sheeting present, likely to contain asbestos, recommend assessment by a licensed asbestos assessor." This is not a finding that will cause most experienced buyers to exit. It is expected language for a pre-1990 home.</p>

      <p>Where it becomes a problem is when buyers receive a building report identifying asbestos without any prior disclosure or context from the vendor. The surprise factor creates anxiety that a simple disclosure upfront would have avoided. Buyers who are told during the sales campaign that the property has an asbestos register available, that bonded asbestos is present in the fibro sheeting, and that it is intact and in good condition, are in a completely different mental position than buyers who discover it for the first time in a post-inspection negotiation. The former group is informed and can price it accordingly. The latter group uses it as a discount lever.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Three approaches: leave it, remediate, or disclose and price</h2>
      <p>For most Brisbane sellers with bonded asbestos in good condition, the right approach is to have an asbestos register prepared, disclose it proactively, and list the property without any remediation work. The cost of preparing a register is modest (typically in the range of a few hundred dollars for a standard residential property) and the benefit is significant. It removes uncertainty, demonstrates that you have taken the responsible approach, and positions asbestos as a managed feature of the property rather than a hidden problem.</p>

      <p>Remediation before listing makes commercial sense in a narrower set of circumstances: where the asbestos is in poor condition and likely to be identified as a significant issue in a building inspection, where you are renovating the property before sale anyway and the removal can be done as part of that work, or where the asbestos is in a location that significantly affects the presentation or marketability of the property. Remediation for its own sake, purely to avoid disclosure, rarely delivers a return that justifies the cost.</p>

      <p>Disclosing and pricing accordingly is always an option, particularly for properties where the asbestos is more extensive, more complex, or where the cost of remediation would be significant. A buyer who understands exactly what remediation will cost and has priced it into their offer is a motivated buyer, not a risk. The worst version of this situation is not a buyer who knows about the asbestos upfront; it is a buyer who discovers it during due diligence after forming a price expectation that did not account for it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Impact on the buyer pool in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>For the pre-1990 properties that dominate much of Brisbane's inner east, including the Queenslander market in Camp Hill, Morningside, Carina, and Norman Park, and the post-war fibro market in Cannon Hill and Tingalpa, buyers are generally well-acquainted with asbestos. Owner-occupiers who are buying a period home and planning to renovate it over time already factor licensed asbestos removal into their renovation budget. Investors with experience in this market understand the material.</p>

      <p>The buyer pool narrows more noticeably with first home buyers who are less familiar with the material, buyers who are securing finance through lenders with stricter asbestos policies (some lenders require a clear asbestos report before approving finance on properties with significant friable asbestos), and buyers who intend to immediately renovate or demolish. For a major renovation or knockdown-rebuild, the presence of extensive asbestos adds cost that needs to be factored into the development economics.</p>

      <p>In none of these cases is asbestos a deal-breaker when handled properly. It is a factor that affects some buyers more than others, and the right disclosure and documentation approach allows each buyer to assess it accurately and proceed on informed terms.</p>

